          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(0)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Because Palantir's valuation relies heavily on terminal value, it is highly sensitive to the discount rate. At an aggressive 15% growth rate and 11% discount rate, the stock is deeply overvalued. If they maintain 35% growth with a 7% discount rate, it's undervalued. This highlights the premium the market places on PLTR's future.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>AIP Hyper-adoption:</strong> If Palantir's Artificial Intelligence Platform (AIP) becomes the de-facto operating system for the Fortune 500, commercial revenue could re-accelerate beyond 50% YoY and stay there.</li>
    <li><strong>Geopolitical Catalysts:</strong> Unforeseen global conflicts heavily drive Palantir's government segment. An escalation could lead to massive unexpected defense contracts globally.</li>
    <li><strong>SaaS Margin Expansion:</strong> If Stock-Based Compensation (SBC) finally trends down to industry norms while gross margins remain ~80%+, cash generation could compound faster than expected.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Valuation Compression:</strong> The market is pricing Palantir for perfection. Any miss in quarterly earnings or guidance could result in a severe multiple contraction, even if the underlying business remains strong.</li>
    <li><strong>Government Concentration:</strong> While commercial is growing, a large portion of revenue is still tied to the US Government. Changes in administration, budget cuts, or shifting defense priorities could cause sudden revenue drops.</li>
    <li><strong>SBC Dilution:</strong> Palantir historically issued significant stock to employees. While they are now GAAP profitable and buying back shares, aggressive SBC acts as a hidden cost that dilutes shareholders over time.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. For a company like Palantir that trades at extreme multiples (e.g. 150x+ Forward P/E), multiples are essentially meaningless for assessing intrinsic value. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, then lets math determine the price based on cash generation.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why a 9% discount rate and not 10% or 11%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents your required return. While higher growth tech usually warrants a higher discount rate, Palantir's lack of debt, incredible net cash position ($6.9B), and the "sticky" recurring revenue of deep government/enterprise integration lower its structural risk compared to a standard SaaS company. 9% balances hyper-growth volatility with fortress-like balance sheet safety.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How often is this updated?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">We update this analysis when Palantir reports quarterly earnings or when material events change the thesis (e.g., major contract wins, macroeconomic shifts).</div>
    </details>
  </div>

